A Quick Exploration of Variants in the 1000 Genome Project

Michael Kane

November 2, 2015

The bash Script to Download Variant Data

# Redo chromosome 12

# Get the variant files.
wget ftp://ftp-trace.ncbi.nih.gov/1000genomes/ftp/release/20130502/ALL.chr*.genotypes.vcf.gz

# Get the genomes phenotype data file
wget ftp://ftp.1000genomes.ebi.ac.uk/vol1/ftp/technical/working/20130606_sample_info/20130606_g1k.ped

# Get the sub and super populations.
wget ftp://ftp.1000genomes.ebi.ac.uk/vol1/ftp/phase3/20131219.populations.tsv

genome_files=`ls ALL.chr*.genotypes.vcf.gz`

for fn in $genome_files; do
  chr_num=`echo $fn | awk -F "." '{print $2}' | sed "s/[^0-9]//g"`
  gunzip -c $fn | sed /^#/d  | cut  -f '10-' | ../a.out | cut -f '1-2' > chr$chr_num.txt
done

Create the Incidence Matrices with bigmemory

library(bigmemory)
library(foreach)
library(doMC)
registerDoMC(cores=6)

ret = foreach(i=1:22, .combine=c, .inorder=TRUE) %dopar% {
  cat("chromosome:", i, "\n")
  dat = read.big.matrix(paste0("genome-files/chr", i, ".txt"), 
                        backingfile=paste0("genome-files/chr", i, ".bin"),
                        descriptorfile=paste0("genome-files/chr", i, ".desc"), 
                        type="integer",
                        sep="\t",
                        header=FALSE)
  NULL
}

Create the Sparse Matrix and Get Summary Stats

library(biganalytics)
library(bigtabulate)
library(ggplot2)

chr = "chr22"
dat = attach.big.matrix(paste0("genome-files/", chr, ".desc"))
cr = colrange(dat)

bs = bigsplit(dat, 1)
set_diff_bs = setdiff(as.character(1:cr[1,2]), names(bs))
print(length(set_diff_bs))/cr[1,2]
## [1] 3185
##         max 
## 0.002886148
qplot(unlist(lapply(bs, length)), geom="histogram") + 
  xlab("Number of Variants") + ylab("Count")
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

qplot(log(1+unlist(lapply(bs, function(x) log(length(x)+1)))), 
  geom="histogram") + 
  xlab("Log Number of Variants") + ylab("Count")
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Plot the Populations differences on Chromosome 22

library(bigmemory)
library(biganalytics)
library(Matrix)
library(irlba)
library(threejs)

dat = attach.big.matrix(paste0("genome-files/", chr, ".desc"))
# Load the sparse matrix from the big.matrix and get the tsvd.
var_mat = sparseMatrix(i=dat[,2], j=dat[,1], x=1.0)
cm = colMeans(var_mat)
tsvd = irlba(var_mat, nv=3, nu=3, tol=0.1, du=rep(1,nrow(var_mat)), ds=1, dv=cm)

# Use Bryan Lewis's code to get the super populations.
ids = readLines(pipe(paste0("gunzip -c genome-files/ALL.", chr, 
  ".phase3_shapeit2_mvncall_integrated_v5a.20130502.genotypes.vcf.gz",
  "  | sed -n /^#CHROM/p | tr '\t' '\n' | tail -n +10")))

ped = read.table("genome-files/20130606_g1k.ped", sep="\t", header=TRUE, 
                 row.names=2)[ids,6,drop=FALSE]

pop = read.table("genome-files/20131219.populations.tsv", sep="\t",header=TRUE)
pop = pop[1:26,]
super = pop[,3]
names(super) = pop[,2]
super = factor(super)

# Map sample sub-populations to super-populations
ped$Superpopulation = super[as.character(ped$Population)]

# 1 - red - AFR - African
# 2 - lime - AMR - Native Central / South American
# 3 - green - EAS - Eastern Asian
# 4 - blue - EUR - European
# 5 - purple - SAS - Indian Subcontinent

# Plot with colors corresponding to super populations
N = length(levels(super))
scatterplot3js(tsvd$u, col=rainbow(N)[ped$Superpopulation], size=0.5)
